public void enterScope(NodeTraversal t) {
    Node declarationRoot = t.getScopeRoot();
    Renamer renamer;
    if (nameStack.isEmpty()) {
      Preconditions.checkState(
          declarationRoot.getType() != Token.FUNCTION ||
          !(rootRenamer instanceof ContextualRenamer));
      Preconditions.checkState(t.inGlobalScope());
      renamer = rootRenamer;
    } else {
      renamer = nameStack.peek();
    }

    if (declarationRoot.getType() == Token.FUNCTION) {
      for (Node c = declarationRoot.getFirstChild().getNext().getFirstChild(); c != null; c = c.getNext()) {
        String name = c.getString();
        renamer.addDeclaredName(name);
      }
      Node functionBody = declarationRoot.getLastChild();
      findDeclaredNames(functionBody, null, renamer);
    } else if (declarationRoot.getType() == Token.CATCH) {
      // Add catch block declarations
      findDeclaredNames(declarationRoot, null, renamer);
    } else {
      // Add block declarations
      findDeclaredNames(declarationRoot, null, renamer);
    }

    // Only push if shouldTraverse did not push for this scope
    if (declarationRoot.getType() != Token.FUNCTION &&
        declarationRoot.getType() != Token.CATCH) {
      nameStack.push(renamer);
    }
}
```

Note: I added a case for Token.CATCH to match the original logic? Original `else if (declarationRoot.getType() != Token.FUNCTION)` would also catch CATCH. So it's okay. But we need to handle CATCH explicitly in the condition to not push. The original `else if` would also execute for CATCH. So I added an `else if (declarationRoot.getType() == Token.CATCH)` to treat it similarly.

But careful: For CATCH, shouldTraverse already pushed a renamer with the catch variable. So we should use that renamer (peek) and add declarations from the catch block. So we should not push. The above code does that.

For other scopes (like blocks), we push.

Now, shouldTraverse and visit remain essentially the same? But we modified enterScope to not push for FUNCTION/CATCH, so the push in shouldTraverse for those is still correct. visit pops for FUNCTION/CATCH, which matches shouldTraverse's push. So no change needed there.

But we need to ensure that for FUNCTION, shouldTraverse still pushes. Yes.

Now, one more issue: In the original `enterScope`, for the case when declarationRoot is FUNCTION and nameStack is empty (global scope), it checks that rootRenamer is not ContextualRenamer. That's fine. Our change uses rootRenamer directly.

